  "prompt": "The bond angle of Sulphur dioxide is greater than that of Ozone. Why?",
  "response": "The bond angle of sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082) is greater than that of ozone (O\u2083) primarily due to differences in their molecular structures and the nature of the lone pairs on the central atoms.\n\nFor sulfur dioxide:\n- Sulfur dioxide has a bent molecular shape with an approximate bond angle of 119.5\u00b0.\n- Sulfur (the central atom) has one lone pair and is bonded to two oxygen atoms.\n- The lone pair on sulfur exerts repulsion, but sulfur\u2019s larger atomic size compared to oxygen allows this repulsion to be slightly less effective in reducing the bond angle.\n\nFor ozone:\n- Ozone has a bent molecular shape with a bond angle of about 116.8\u00b0.\n- Oxygen (the central atom) has one lone pair and is bonded to two other oxygen atoms.\n- The lone pair on the central oxygen atom in ozone exerts a stronger repulsion due to oxygen\u2019s smaller atomic size and higher electronegativity compared to sulfur.\n- Additionally, oxygen atoms are more electronegative, which increases electron density around the central atom, leading to greater repulsion forces that push the bonding pairs closer together, resulting in a smaller bond angle.\n\nIn summary, the larger atomic size and lower electronegativity of sulfur in SO\u2082 compared to oxygen in O\u2083 contribute to the greater bond angle observed in sulfur dioxide.",
